segments.text: Okay, we were talking about incorporation, and I had a question about Bryan.
Since Bryan was a major city, it was possible that you could be annexed.
Did the residents around there not want?
Cottage station residents did not want to be incorporated in the city of Bryan, and they opposed it, at least actively and verbally.
It never came to the matter of law.
Now, when I started the development of North Oakwood addition, which we spoke of a while ago on the north side of the campus, that area, of course, lay between Bryan and College Station.
And I was sending the property mostly to College Station people.
And they did not want to be.
When I say they, I'm not trying to speak for all of them.
They had a little division of groups.
But College Station would just get out of the way.
They had no tax system, no system of giving utilities and the usual city services that you get from towns, like maintenance of streets and things.
Brian did.
They offered to take care of the street development, install the streets better than I had, and the utilities, particularly sewer system.
So I arranged to have a vote.
We might have had, oh, I had 200, 300 lots in there.
but probably, oh, maybe 50 people, 50 families, perhaps, lived in there.
I just called them together and took a vote where they wanted to make an application to come in the city, College Station city limits or Bryan.
And they voted unanimously for Bryan because, yeah.
See, Texas Avenue was a dirt road at that time, and they was building about an 8 or 10-inch water main from the city limits clearing on the outskirts.
out along this barbecue place, Landy Sims Barbecue.
So they voted for that and we went into that system then.
And of course I promoted it as best I could because that way we had this out-of-town tax system again.
And
It was getting hard to handle.
Had to take care of that.
Now there's a young heroic man by the name of Jim Astin.
Oh, yes.
City manager?
Huh?
City manager of Bryan?
Yeah.
He was city manager of Bryan.
Very aggressive young man and brilliant, smart man.
He was president of the Republic Bank in Dallas, which is the only Republic Bank here.
Oh, I didn't know that.
Yeah.
He was a great athlete out of A&M, a little after my time.
I was 29, he was about 33.
But, see, I owned the utility lines.
I owned the streets.
I hadn't even dedicated them to the public.
I owned, that is, Oakwood Rent-A-Cup, because my own Oakwood Rent-A-Cup.
So he propositioned me to buy those utility lines.
Well, I said, doggone anxious to get rid of them.
And I'd have probably given them to him if he had asked me.
But he paid me $30,000 or $40,000.
Oh, really?
Which would be $300,000 or $400,000 now.
Oh.
That's what inflation is then.
And of course, that made it possible for me to do other things out there that I'd been wanting to do.
So then, by that time, then I dedicated the streets to the public.
So the public owned the streets, like county roads and streets and cities and such.
And it's after that that the residents decided to ask to be annexed into Bryan?
Yes.
OK. Well, what about the residents around College Station, around the A&M campus?
Why didn't they want to be annexed to Bryan?
Was there any?
Oh, I hardly know the word to use.
Not necessarily stubbornness.
They just wanted their own town.
They wanted their own town.
They just wanted their own town.
And they'd always lived outside of Bryan.
They didn't want to be any part of Bryan, and still don't.
Yeah, that's right.
If you want to get yourself in a terrible row, you can go out here and start making speeches.
Let's join Bryan.
Either chambers of commerce.
Maybe you read lately.
Now, see, we had two separate chambers of commerce for a long time.
But after the war, I guess World War II, they joined the two chambers together.
and have one, Bryan College Station.
But now there's some agitation for Bryan College Station to have its own chamber of commerce.
I don't like that.
I don't see it either.
Well, they have different offices, don't they?
Oh, yeah.
But they're one.
So basically, they just wanted their own town, felt like they could best provide for their own needs.
Well, you were living in College Station at that time?
I've always lived in College Station.
Were you in favor of incorporation then?
Were you in Negroes?
College Station?
Yes, indeed.
I certainly was, yeah.
I promoted every way I could, except as being an officer.
I never was a councilman or mayor or anything like that.
But I certainly used what little influence I had to promote the city of College Station.
The cemetery, for example.
I promoted that cemetery.
You were president of the cemetery.
Yeah.
Well, I owned the land.
I owned the land at one time.
Well, can you tell me about that?
Well, yeah.
I was real active in business enterprises, well, from the middle 30s on.
The war developed, as I was telling you, on the south side when the Japs raided Barrel Harbor.
I knew I was going to have to go in the war, because I had a commission as a reserve officer.
I was first lieutenant in infantry.
So right at the beginning of that dark Sunday day, I began to make plans to be called.
And I was.
And I went in April of 42, just two or three months later.
Well, we didn't have anything out in Amabank.
Just didn't have any facilities at all.
And we needed a bank, needed a bank.
And I was the principal, because I had this construction going on down there.
And I'd average, make one trip a day, at least, to Bryan Bank.
And of course, get my payroll over there on Fridays.
And I had done a little work on the bank.

I got a good deal of discouragement from that, but then I was caught up and forgot about it when I spent about two and a half years in Europe during the war while I was in the Air Corps in a heavy bombardment outfit.
And I used to ride home to my wife and some other friends and tell them the things we had to do when the war was over.
If you got back.
And my first priority was that bank.
That was the bank, which is the University of Nashville now.
That was the first priority.
And the second was a hotel or something.
We didn't have, we had the Blue Bonnet Motel over at the East Gate, little wooden shacks, about eight or ten of them, called the Blue Bonnet.
And that's the only facilities we had for overnight people.
Had the LaSalle Hotel and Bride, you know, and then we didn't have a cemetery.
And I, during my experience, had come up that we needed a cemetery out there.
We had to go to Barron Brothers County, had to be in Bryan, you know.
A lot of people came to Illinois and other states, they'd ship the bodies back there to Barron.
Those were my, well, those were my first three priorities.
Another one we had to have was a hardware store.
I was in the building business and I had to go to get a pound of nails.
Everything that I eat, I had to go to Brian.
I was wearing a Rhodes hat.
Well, when the war ended, I wrote to 50 people or something like that to have a meeting on the bank.
We had the meeting.
And not the charter for the bank.
We measured from May the 1st, 1946.
I got in October of 45.
Then, now as for the hotel, the student center, I joined with a former student, and we created and raised the money for the student center.
And it had, oh, say, 100 rooms in it for a guest, you know, for a hotel.
And I never could conceive of never needing any more rooms than that.
So that took care of that.
So you were... Goodbye, honey.
Bye-bye.
See you tomorrow.
Nice to meet you.
You were involved in the student center meeting?
And through the former student association, I was active with the former students, not individually.
I mean, don't say that you couldn't say that I helped create it.
I worked with the students to raise the money to get it done.
And that solved that problem.
Then my next one was the cemetery.
You know where it is.
Right.
I got a little committee together.
including Mr. F.W.
Hensel, who was an architect, a landscape architect, and went down and bought the lands from 50 acres by Mr. Gorisky.
And that's where the cemetery is.
G-O-R-I-S-K-Y, something like Gorisky.
And that's where the cemetery is now.
Now, I had the cooperation...
from the university, at least through President Gilchrist.
He was president of the university at that time, and he was very eager to have a cemetery out here.
And I got some ideas from him.
I was going to lay it off in sections, one for presidents, a little section where only presidents would be buried.
And perhaps you didn't know that down across the railroad track
You know what's called a hard liquor track?
Right across from it, there's a cemetery over there with one prison buried in it.
Who was that?
I can't say his name.
But you've got a little tombstone down there with this marker.
It's still down there?
Yeah.
Because I read that they had tried to make arrangements to move all the bodies down there to the cemetery.
Did they not ever, did that ever...
They never did do that.
They were going to when they...
When they built the dormitories, number what, dormitory 20 or 30 or 40 or whatever the numbers are, you know where they are.
Over there on the, by the drill field.
There's two or three graves there, and they moved them.
And they moved them down there to this place I'm talking about.
I don't think there's any presence in them.
There was a grave by the drill field that's on Canyon Campus?
Yes.
That's at Westgate?
Is it at Westgate, the drill field?
Is it at Westgate?
Is it what, honey?
At Westgate.
Oh, no.
No, it's a, let me see.
Well, you know where the president's home is.
Yes.
That cross toward me.
The Texas Avenue?
The big open space?
That's where... Where the mess hall?
Right.
The graves used to be there?
Yeah.
Okay.
And they moved them to across the railroad tracks.
Right.
Uh-huh.
Wasn't but two or three.
But the present now, how his grave ever got over, I never found out.
But I thought it was pitiful that him to be over there.
And nobody knew anything about it.
And I ran an ad in the Texas Aggie that anybody knew any of the relatives of this present
that I described before he was, and he was over there alone by himself, and kind of pitiful and not like to move his body, and we had to go through some law to get him to move a body.
And I finally found a distant relative in Abilene, and had some correspondence with him, but he faded.
I don't know whatever happened.
But anyway, that's when we got the cemetery, that Mr. Gilchrist was ready for it.
But when we took it up to the city of Cotton Station, I said, I'm going to have a private cemetery, develop it myself, sell the cemetery lots, which is common.
A lot of the better cemeteries are that way.
But the city of Cotton Station bust up.
They wouldn't go in on it.
So I said, well, do you want the cemetery?
Yes, we do.
So I sold them the land.
And that's where the cemetery is now.
Oh, I see.
That was my second priority.
And weren't you on the cemetery committee that decided?
Well, locating it, I didn't have anything to do with designing the lots and laying out the rules and regulations in that cemetery.
Do you remember, I had heard something to the extent of on that land, it's a huge tract,
And then part of it was already...
There's a little place in there.
Perhaps an acre.
That land belongs to this family whose name I gave you.
I don't know from how long, way back in 1875 or something like that.
Their religion was Methodist.
And they gave the...
National Methodist Association, the whole thing, not just the local Methodist.
An acre or two acres, whatever's in there, and it's still there.
Those old markers are still in there.
Is that what they refer to as Old Shiloh Cemetery?
That's right.
Is that just that acre?
Or, okay, I was curious.
It had steel fence around it.
I haven't been down there lately to see if that steel fence is still there.
But they still own that.
Oh, it doesn't belong to the city?
No.
Oh, I thought it did, but it belongs to the Methodist Church.
To the Methodist Church.
That's interesting.
Yeah.
Okay.
I was going to ask some more questions about incorporation.
You were in favor of it, and do you remember who pushed the hardest for incorporation?
Do you remember the meetings?
Well, probably.
I can't probably...
Mr. Ernest Langford was one.
Mr. Ernest Langford was a mayor for, oh, quite long.
I don't know how long.
But he was head of the architecture department.
Mr. Hensel, F.W.
Hensel, he was a landscape architect, a wonderful gentleman, a great friend of mine.
We worked together on the city.
Did he help your, I had read that he had helped College Park, had helped kind of landscape College Park.
Did he do that for Oakwood, or?
No, I didn't use it on Oakwood.
North Oakwood, he designed it, laid it out in lots and lots, but we didn't have to actually do any architecture, decoration, and things like that.
But he worked on the College Station Cemetery.
Oh, that's right.
Yeah, he worked on that.
A man named Joe Orr, who was a civil engineer, he probably surveyed it out, put those postmarks, you know, around the corner.
That's right.
I read that he did that.
the only one that comes to me right now.
But we got the cemetery and the bank and the hotel and finally got a hardware store out there.
What hardware?
It was called Lloyd Smith Hardware at the time.
It's over there at the North Gate.
You know where the Baptist Church is?
The building right across the street from the Baptist Church.
It was a brick building.
That's where we put Lloyd Smith in the hardware business.
I got it financed for him through my connections.
And that was so probably 19...
He was there before the war, about 1941 or two, something like that.
No, I mean after the war, right after the war.
And then I kind of put myself and my own business in, operating the thing.
Got the bank going, as I told you, and it went broke.
Oh, okay.
I want to ask you about the bank, but let's see.
Before I do...
You were talking about your building at Southside.
Was it called Burgess Building?
It's referred to that.
Yes, uh-huh.
Did you lease part of it to the city as city offices?
Yes, you're sure right.
Mr.
Colonel Anderson mentioned that this morning when I talked to him.
See, they leased.
The city of College Station had one office up there.
I had operated three offices, and the city had one.
Oh, I see.
I had my own little private office in an architecture.
Art Tech had an office.
And then we had an insurance office up there, too.
And how long did they rent the city out?
Well, the city left there pretty soon after World War II.
They built a property over on the north side, down by the railroad track.
Uh-huh.
The first city office?
Yeah.
They built their own property down there and moved out down there about
War was over in 45, probably in 47 or something like that they moved out.
Apparently they were at Northgate, in an office at Northgate, and then they moved into your building?
Yes, they had a little, just one little room there at the Northgate.
I don't remember how much it was, but I built that building there on the south side.
They moved down there, and they were there five, six years.
Okay, and then they moved into their offices.
Yeah.
And you were telling me earlier about College Station, then when they incorporated, they bought the lines, your utility, your sewer, your water, your...
Right.
They bought them from the developer themselves?
Well, from the open-ready company that owned them.
Yeah, I put those utilities in there.
And was this the case for all of the divisions that were...
Well, there really wasn't one at that time, not just me.
At that time, when I bought those lots from College Park, then I got the whole business.
And our tourist disposal plant ran out across
Well, we had a disposal bed, not very far from where the present high school, College Station High School is.
Way off down there, you know.
Oh, the present one.
Yeah.
Okay.
We had a disposal system down there.
And the city bought all of that from you?
Yeah.
Uh-huh.
Put it in their own system.
Now they carry it way on down across Highway 6.
Way off down there.
That's what the...
That's where the present disposal system is, way off down there.
Highway 6 says you're going out of town, or Highway 6 says you're going out of town?
Yeah, it goes in that facility.
Oh, I'll have to look for it.
Can you see it on the side of the road?
Oh, no, honey, it's way off down in the sticks.
Okay.
Well, after the city became incorporated, how adequate were the services?
I mean, did you feel like there was an increase?
Oh, yeah.
As far as fire?
Sure, yeah.
Well, they just had people that would do the job.
I didn't have anybody employed except a garbage man to pick up.
If we had electrical trouble, I had to hire a private electrician to go down there and do whatever was necessary.
And the electric company, of course, was getting that from A&M, too.
They installed the poles and the wiring and made the inspections and such as that.
That the city did that, you're saying?
When the city was organizing, they took over all that.
They took over that.
How about the schools?
Did you feel like, do you have children?
Yes.
Did you feel like the schools provided education?
Yes, they had excellent schools, high schools.
In fact, we always felt, it might have been a little jealousy or something, we felt our educational services for children exceeded Brian's because I had many teachers.
Most of the teachers were
husbands and wives of the college staff.
They were highly trained, you know.
And what about the upkeep of roads?
Well, when the city organized it, of course they took over the upkeep of the roads.
Before the city, we just had to do it as it needed, yeah.
And so you felt like it improved?
Oh yes, it greatly improved.
Did you feel like the council was responsible, responsive to the needs of the citizens?
Yes, the council, we've always had a very fine council in this city.
They were politicians, you know.

It's like any other politician, but they were educated people, and they were devoted to their job, and they wanted to do what they're supposed to do to maintain the comfort and ease and the peace of getting around.
I think the College Station area has been particularly fortunate in having that kind of people to serve as the mayors and councilmen, as we do today.
Very high class people.
Do you feel like they've shown, in the past, they've shown a lot of foresight as far as planning?
Absolutely.
They sure have.
Yeah.
You mentioned Colonel Anderson before, and so I was going to ask you,

some information you are friends with Mr. Anderson oh yeah he's one of my most beloved old gentlemen he's a track coach one of the athletic coaches here he's a fine athlete himself from Mississippi came here about with Mr. D.X.
Bible about 1919 after World War I he was an officer in World War I
And he got the title of colonel in World War I?
Well, I think he was a captain or maybe a major when he came out of the service, but he stayed in the reserves and was promoted to colonel.
And he was called back in duty in World War II, but he didn't stay very long.
He was asked to be relieved, getting old.
I think he's 90 and 91 now.
Oh, he is.
Oh, my heavens.
I want to give you his number if you don't mind, Judge.
Do you have his number anywhere?
No, sir.
Telephone number.
And he's awful proud of being married one time.
That's what I'd like to talk to him about.
He didn't believe in taxes.
Don't you dare say Mr. Burgess said you didn't believe in taxes.
Don't say that.
But when he was married, he didn't want any taxes.
Not even property taxes?
No.
I've kidded him about this many times.
He can take it.
I'm kind of kidding you.
But he lived down there on Fairview Street.
Mm-hmm.
bought a house from the college and moved it down there.
And I sold him the property.
And those were dirt streets, gravel top, you know.
And a little hole developed out there, probably as big as an ordinary wash tub.
Not that deep, of course, but water stood in it for days and days.
And some smart-aleck people down there put a little sign up there.
No fishing allowed by order of Colonel Anderson.
And he saw that, and he had no real automobile, and you wouldn't know about that either.
And a two-wheel trailer, he was going behind it.
He went out somewhere and drove right up, and that thing fell to the ground and fell in his fishing hole.
They took his sign down.
I'll kid you about that.
Oh, how funny.
That is funny.
We talked earlier about zoning, and apparently zoning has always been very important in college stations.
Yes, right from the very beginning.
Did you like that idea of zoning, and why?
Well, because you could control the type of house and what was to be done to it.
My addition, the Oakwood addition, was the first area between Dallas
And I got that from the FHA, this man, I tell you that.
You had to, as a residential area, that's what it was.
We not only controlled by a contract, I'd give you a deed to the property, and that kind of contract, what you could do with that property.
You had to build a house so many feet from the sideline, so many feet from the front line, and it had to be certain square feet of area, say a minimum of 1,200 square feet.
That's just an ordinary, a very ordinary two or three bedroom house.
See?
It controlled the size of the house and architectural design.
and where it'd be located on the lot.
You couldn't go closer than 30 feet to the street line.
Meet sidelines, I remember 12 feet, meet sidelines.
So it makes the area look nicer.
Well, yeah.
Well, Bryan has never adopted zoning.
They have no zoning.
Do you know why they didn't adopt zoning?
Well, they just never did when they organized the town way back there.
Now, there's certain additions to the city of Bryan.
For example, my North Oakwood addition is in the city of Bryan, but it's highly zoned.
It's highly zoned.
A lot more than the South Oakwood addition is.
And of course, that helps sell that thing.
It helps sell it.
Because people know they're going to have homes.
You couldn't have an automobile shop next door to you or something else.
It had to be a single family residence.
But just because Bryan was started
earlier in the history that it was really never adopted?
Yeah, Rydler started about 1800 and what, 40?
Somewhere in the 40s.
Very old.
And they never dreamed of zoning.
They never had it in their mind.
You call a peace property, you do what you want to with it.
And of course, we had a little trouble with that, especially in North Oakwood, on rooming houses and one thing or another.
One doctor was going to sue me.
And I invite him to.
Let's see if these things any good.
Let's do it on a friendly basis.
You just sue me, and we'll see how we come out.
Well, of course, by that time, Zoni had become very popular, and it was popular out there.
A lot of people bought it from me out there because it was on.
Excuse me.
I don't remember where we were on the bank.
I substantially organized that by letters to friends who were overseas during the war.
I was in Europe.
And when I came home, I got home in October of 45.
I might say I just hit the ground running.
And we obtained a charter.
We had some opposition in getting a charter from other banks in the area.
Uh-huh.
We didn't have an institution out here at all, any banking institution at all.
Had to go to buying.
And it was an awful nuisance, as much as we were doing.
So we got a bank, called it the College Station State Bank, and capitalized it.
But we couldn't get any building material because it had to have priorities from the veterans coming home from service.
Everything you'd have to get a...
I had a word for it, I can't say it.
But you'd get a little form for building material.
And some of it wasn't available at all, except to a veteran.
And we were able to get a little...
hut that was 16 feet, well, not very much bigger than this hall office right here.
This looks like it may be 12 by 12 or something.
We got two of them, put them together, and made 16 by 32.
It was a plywood building.
We could almost cut it up with a knife.
That was our first bank site.
We opened the bank and started business.
Where was the umpane?
It was over there on Jersey Street at the North Gate.
Excuse me.
I think the Presbyterian owned that building there.
And I forget what it's called.
It's a solid concrete building.
You know where Wyatt's, what is that little concrete building next to Wyatt's?
That bookstore there, sporting goods store, whatever it is.
That was the building.
That was the bank until we bid it where it is now.
It's a university national now.
We changed from a state bank to a national bank.
I was one of the originators of the bank, served on its original board, and was the vice president and executive officer.
The bank went broke.
I had a man in there running it that had been on the examining course.
And I thought it was awful lucky to be able to get him.
But he just didn't have what it takes to make a banker, couldn't control his loans, and lost all of our capital.
And we had to reorganize the bank.
And I was one of the principal organizers.
the commissioner wouldn't let the man we had running it come back in there at all.
And I never had the bank experience, but they wouldn't let anybody else run except me.
So I went in and operated the bank about, oh, eight months or a year myself and rebuilt it, reassessed our stockholders for some money to rebuild the capital.
And this was University National?
Shortly after that, we changed it from a state bank to a national bank, and we called it the University National.
And we got the bank back on its feet, and it's been doing very well since then.
That's wonderful.
Do you remember the man's name?
Lamar Fly.
Oh, yeah, I've heard that.
Yes, Lamar Fly was a wonderful fellow.
He grew up in a bank in Houston.
It was a whole state bank, I believe they called it.
Anyway, his father ran the bank.
He just grew up in it.
Got a banking degree from Texas University and was an examiner, National Examining Force.
And I thought we was awful lucky to get him.
And it was.
He knew what he was doing, but he just didn't have any intestinal fortitude to talk to people.
Right, it takes that.
They could just do him any way they wanted to, and they found that out pretty quick.
He lost the capital of the bank, of course, and that just ruined us.
What year was it that you had to reorganize?
I read that you were the president of the Chamber of Commerce in its early years, is that right?
Yes, they had a local Chamber of Commerce out here.
and I was the president of it.
Was Bryan and Constitution one chamber of commerce then?
No.
No, they were two.
That's when they separated.
I was also a vice-president of the Bryan Chamber.
I'd been a chamber of commerce man all my business life.
Do you like the fact that it is bringing in industry?
Well, I'd have to say I do, being a businessman.
I'm getting up to an age where I like peace and quiet.
But I know that we've got to prepare for the future of this community, for the future people in it.
And I believe that College Station and Brasses County as a whole is really on a boom.
And I think it's going to hold.
Do you like the way that the character of the town has changed?
Do you see the character of the town changing?
Well, I can't say that I really like it, but if you ask me why, I couldn't answer that.
I wouldn't want to try to make any move.
For example, Bryan, as you know, the town of Bryan, the main street, is dead.
Oh, yeah.
And that's kind of sad.
But it's brought it on itself.
We just got to give in to progress.
These little malls that scattered around, they're so new to us, to me, that I can't conceive of them really continuing on an exciting success.
You've got little stores scattered around here, and another mile or two, another batch of stores, you know?
Right.
Oh, I agree.
I don't see how it could go, but it is.
It seems every time somebody starts one, it fills up with business houses.
As far as the people are concerned, was it more of a tight-knit group in the early days because of its size?
No, I don't think it's any particular group.
I think that the times just sort of developed itself.
It just naturally developed.
A person would go out here, and this land
for development purposes, awfully high, high priced.
Then you've got the expense of development, subdividing it into lots and blocks.
Given ordinary residential section, say, of 100 acres, probably at least 20 acres will be in streets where you can't sell.
You have to give it away.
Well, of course, the other property, you could put lots in there.
Those lots carry the cost of the property that you're giving away.
And it's expensive.
When a man goes to buy a lot to build on, it's high.
High priced.
But then the big money in the land is the commercial development of it.
If it's located where it can have a store or two, a little shopping center, they can get several times the price per square foot on commercial property than they can get for residential property.
So that encourages the developer to
to develop a little commercial site wherever he is.
I did that way back there.
My first one was on the south side that we spoke of a while ago.
when I had to get ahead of the city of College Station.
I didn't really know what I was doing, but I knew that the best way for me to come out on that property was to sell the commercial property at a high price.
Right, that's right.
And it's still working that way.
You see the town going in that direction more, more in a commercial area?
Yeah.
